o college. However, these dreams of upward mobility are often dashed by the difficulty of trying to get by on meager wages. In accessible and engaging prose, It’s Not Like I’m Poor examines the costs and benefits of the new work-based safety net, suggesting ways to augment its strengths so that more of the working poor can realize the promise of a middle-class life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aPublic welfarezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aTax creditszUnited States. 0aWorking poorzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aamerican dream.  aamerican politics.  aamerican poverty.  aannual cash windfall.  abuilding savings.  acareer.  aearned income tax credit.  afamily.  afinances.  agoing back to school.  ainvestment in the future.  alow earnings.  alow wage jobs.  ameager wages.  amiddle class life.  amoney and power.  amoney.  apolicy analysis.  apolitics.  apoor.  apoverty.  apublic policy.  asending kids to college.  asocial relations.  ataxes.  aupward mobility.  awages.  awealth.  awelfare checks.  awelfare reform.  awelfare.  awork based safety net.  aworking parents.  aworking poor.1 aEdin, Kathryn, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aTach, Laura, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052027534840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095922440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520959224423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520959224/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter